The Impact of Incarceration in Childhood on Adulthood Coping Behaviors and Mental Health

BMIN503/EPID600 Final Project

Author

Morgan Watson

1 Overview

The goal of this project is to determine the association between experiencing an arrest in childhood and adverse health outcomes in adulthood. The project is focused on mental health outcomes, such as depression and suicidality. To better understand the potential relationship, the influence of certain coping mechanisms (alcohol and substance use) will be assessed. The question will be addressed using publicly available Wave I and Wave IV data from the National Longitudinal Study of Adolescent to Adult Health (Add Health Study). Through discussion with Dr.Â Elizabeth Nesoff, I was able to specify my question to examine relevant risky behaviors and mental health outcomes. Additionally, I determined an analysis strategy with Dr.Â Nick Seewald to conduct logistic regression on my binary health and behavior outcomes.

GitHub Repository: https://github.com/moewatson/BMIN503_Final_Project

2 Introduction

Experience with incarceration has been associated with a variety of negative health outcomes, ranging from chronic health conditions to infectious diseases to mental health (1). It is important to understand how involvement with the justice system at critical developmental periods can impact health in adulthood. Through investigating the relationship between childhood arrest/incarceration, adverse coping mechanisms, and health outcomes, this affect can be better understood.

In 2022, there were more than 1.2 million adults detained in prison (2). There were over 420,000 youth arrests made in 2020 and more than 25,000 children under the age of 18 were held in various juvenile justice facilities (3,4). While there are fewer children involved with the justice system than adults, children experience the system at an important period of development. It is necessary to understand the potential lasting effects of the justice system given the multitude of health factors and magnitude of individuals impacted by the system. Adverse Childhood Experiences (ACEs) are potentially traumatic events which have been linked to a multitude of health outcomes. ACEs fall under three categories: Abuse (physical, emotional, or sexual), Neglect (physical or emotional), and Household Challenges (incarceration, mental illness, substance misuse or dependence, intimate partner violence, or parental separation/divorce) (5). More than 60% of US adults report experiencing at least one ACE before reaching 18 (6). Experiencing ACEs are associated with higher risk of chronic diseases, substance use, and poor mental health (4). Further, past studies have found an association between childhood arrest and increased suicidality as well as an association between childhood incarceration and worse general health (7,8). More research is needed to understand the long-lasting impacts of the carceral system on health.

This project is interdisciplinary as it ties together factors from the fields of epidemiology, criminology, and sociology to assess a complex issue. Individuals can become connected to the justice system through societal, community, interpersonal, and individual reasons. In order to determine how to effectively reduce the negative results of incarceration, interventions need to be developed which address the variety of avenues creating risk factors. Epidemiology helps to understand the magnitude of incarcerations effect on health. Sociology provides context into how people live and the factors which impact their decisions and opportunities in life. Finally, criminology offers specific insights into the justice system and how it operates. Dr.Â Nesoff provided important knowledge related to how oneâs neighborhood context can affect substance use and other risky behaviors. She assisted me in framing this project within the field of social epidemiology. Dr.Â Seewald provided helpful suggestions for my analysis, especially related to the usage of a Bonferroni correction in order to address the possibility of Type I Error when running multiple hypothesis tests within the same study.

3 Methods

Public-use data from the Add Health study will be analyzed below. Wave 1 data was collected in 1994-95 when participants were in grades 7-12 and first recruited into the study. Wave 4 data was collected in 2008 when participants were aged 24-32. Wave V data has been collected, but is not yet publically available. In Wave 4, participants answered questions about criminal justice history and personal health. This data allows for information to be gathered the about experience with the justice system in childhood and current (adulthood) health. It is important to note the role of temporality in this data and subsequent analysis. In order to ensure that the health outcomes occurred after the exposure of the justice system, only questions with a time component will be considered in the final analysis. These time components include the following: âIn the last 30 daysâ, âIn the last 7 daysâ, âIn the previous 12 monthsâ, etc. Questions which include the wording such as, âhave you everâ, will not be used for the final analysis.

In order to answer the research question, relevant demographic, exposure, and outcome variables will be selected from the original data. Any categorical variables will be recoded as factors with descriptive levels. For analysis, some variables will be dichotomized. After the cleaning of the data, various descriptive statistics will be presented through tables and figures. Finally, logistic and linear regression models will be utilized to analyze the data. Both unadjusted and adjusted models will also be presented after applying an accurate Bonferroni correction to account for potential type I error.

The data for this project will utilize information from Wave 1 and Wave 4. Wave 1 includes necessary, self-reported, baseline information of participant sex and race as well as parent information (education and income) which will be used as covariates. Wave 4 includes self-reported information on criminal justice history, health history, and current health. Since this is a longitudinal analysis, demographic information from the adult participants cannot be used to also adjust for childhood experiences. For example, having a college degree as an adult (Wave 4) does not influence the likelihood of being arrested as a youth.

The necessary outcome variables are recoded above. While there are many variables related to health and health behaviors, the regression analysis will be focused on only those for which temporality can be established. Specifically, questions in the Wave 4 questionnaire worded as âhave you ever been told by a doctorâ will not be included in the ultimate analysis because it is unknown when the diagnosis occurred. Instead, variables which asked about health outcomes within the past 30 days, or past 7 days for depression, will be used to assess the longitudinal relationship between childhood arrest/incarceration and adulthood health. Since most of the outcome variables are categorical, the ones which will be used in the analysis have been dichotomized so that logistic regression can be conducted. The outcome variables which will be used in the final analysis are: general health, BMI, counseling status, depressive symptoms (based on the CESD-10), suicidal thoughts, use of the cigarettes/alcohol/marijuana in the last 30 days.

final_data <- merge(w1_comp_var, w4_comp_fctvar, by = "AID")

3.4.2 Regression Function

#develop function to run regression models and generate ORs and CIs
model_OR <- function(formula) {
  mod <- glm(formula, family = binomial, data = final_data)
  summary(mod)
  odds_ratio = exp(coef(mod))
  confidence = exp(confint(mod))
  outcome <- as.character(formula[[2]])
  results <- data.frame(
    outcome = outcome,
    variable = names(odds_ratio),
    odds_ratio = odds_ratio,
    lower_ci = confidence[,1],
    upper_ci = confidence[,2]
  )
  results <- results |>
    filter(variable == "child_arrest_jailYes")
  print(results)
  return(results)
}

bon_OR <- function(formula) {
  mod <- glm(formula, family = binomial, data = final_data)
  summary(mod)
  odds_ratio = exp(coef(mod))
  confidence = exp(confint(mod, level = 0.99))
  outcome <- as.character(formula[[2]])
  results <- data.frame(
    outcome = outcome,
    variable = names(odds_ratio),
    odds_ratio = odds_ratio,
    lower_ci = confidence[,1],
    upper_ci = confidence[,2]
  )
  results <- results |>
    filter(variable == "child_arrest_jailYes")
  print(results)
  return(results)
}

The following functions were developed to run the various logistic regression models required for the final analysis. Since this project examines the same exposure on a multitude of outcomes, the probability of experiencing a type I error is high. A type I error is the occurrence of a false positive, or when an association is found to be significant when it is not in reality. The probability of experiencing this error becomes very large the more hypothesis tests, or regression analyses, are run. As such, in addition to conducting standard logistic regression models, the regression has also been run while including a Bonferroni Correction. The Bonferroni Correction generates a more conservative alpha value to be used to assess significance of an association. It is typically calculated by dividing the standard alpha value, typically 0.05, by the number of tests being run. For this project there are 8 total associations being tested. The Bonferroni-corrected significance value is 0.05/8 = 0.00625. In order to develop the needed confidence intervals for the odds ratios, a significance value of 0.005 was utilized and 99% confidence intervals were created.

Even with the Bonferroni correction, all of the assessed unadjusted associations are significant. Those who experienced an arrest or incarceration before age 18 had 0.58 times the odds of experiencing a health rating of Excellent/Good than those who were not arrested or incarcerated in childhood. Individuals who had a childhood arrest or incarceration had greater odds of psychological/emotional counseling, depressive symptoms, suicidal thoughts, cigarette usage, alcohol usage, and marijuana usage than those who did not experience childhood arrest or incarceration.

5 Conclusion

Based on the above results, it can be concluded that there seems to be a positive association between experience with the carceral system before age 18 and negative health outcomes. Specifically, participants who were arrested or incarcerated before the age of 18 had lower odds of reporting that they considered their health Excellent or Good. Additionally, they were associated with worse mental health outcomes such as high depressive symptoms and suicidal thoughts. They also utilized cigarettes, alcohol, and marijuana more than individuals who did not experience arrest or incarceration in childhood. When considering the descriptive tables, it seems as though individuals with the exposure were more likely to have utilized drugs at some point in their lives. They also had higher rates of diagnosed health outcomes such as diabetes, ptsd, and adhd. The most common reason for childhood arrest was theft or an alcohol-related charge.

6 Discussion

There were several limitations to this project. First, in order to establish temporality, the analysis relied on self-reported outcome measures and not diagnosed outcomes. The reliance on self-reported data leads to the possibility of information bias. Specifically, there is likely recall bias from having to provide information about the exposure, which occurred before the age of 18, when the participant was 26-32. Additionally, the outcome variables utilized time points such as âWithin the last 30 daysâ which can impact recall bias. Since the variables of interest include highly sensitive topics such as the criminal justice system and substance use, there is a possibility for the occurrence of social desirability bias. The accuracy of their answers cannot be guaranteed. The results of this project are not currently representative of the general population since the necessary Add Health sample weights were not applied.

These initial results highlight that it is important to better understand the association between childhood arrest/incarceration and adulthood behaviors and health. Next steps might include conducting the above analyses separately for both arrest and incarceration to determine which might be more influential on health. Investigating the potential dose-response of different coping behaviors might provide a deeper understanding into the impact of childhood arrest/incarceration. Finally, past studies have demonstrated an association between substance use and adverse physical and mental health outcomes. As such, it would be interesting to determine the potential mediating or modifying role of coping behaviors on the relationship between childhood arrest/incarceration and health. This knowledge could inform future interventions to limit the influence of childhood experience with the justice system on health.
